When we arrived at Spring Valley Guest Ranch for a lunch break, the owner Jim Saville mentioned that he had heard the whinny of the eastern screech owl near the creek north of his house earlier in the spring. We walked there but got no reply to playing its call.  When we returned to the house and played the call, Stan Shadick immediately saw a grey phase bird fly across his back yard and sit in a tree long enough for all 5 of us to see it. I obtained photos. We noticed its distinctive size with short ear tufts, grey colour with black markings on face. John Patterson later recorded its whinny call after it flew north towards the creek.  Some farm workers mentioned that they had heard the call that morning near the house.

Observation Details: Had heard reports of a Screech owl being within a couple blocks of the Park, one morning my Mom and I decided to get up and be out just as the sun was coming up to hopefully successfully locate This owl in the park. As we were heading down the boardwalk I quickly became impatient when we didn’t hear or see anything in the first few minutes,  and went off the path to capture photos of the sun starting to rise (I wasn’t very patient back then, haha). As I was shooting the sunrise, I heard my mom quietly calling for me. As I got back onto the boardwalk, I noticed this little grey ball of fluff with bright green eyes, bouncing from branch to branch in a low tree just a couple meters away from her. it was still rather dark out, so as I got closer I could slowly start seeing more details, like light barring across the chest and stomach, a light green beak and big green eyes, from this I could successfully I.D it as an Eastern Screech-Owlet. As we observed the little one branch, it slowly began heading higher up into the tree’s. as it makes it way up, it accompanied 3 other Owlets that had been perched not 20 feet above us the whole time and began to roost for the day. Knowing that there were 4 owlets around, we figured it was a safe bet there would be an adult, or maybe even a pair somewhere nearby. We started thoroughly examining trees, and roughly 25 feet back (15 or so feet from the owlets) was a Brown Morph adult ESO perched on a broken tree limb tight to the trunk, preening and observing the owlets from afar. I moved a branch slightly to get a better view of the adult owl before she let out a whinny call, the next second I heard an identical call come from roughly 10-20 feet behind me, I couldn’t get a visual. But from the way the ESO we could see looked over, and the identical call, it was safe to assume the mate was on the other side of the boardwalk in the trees ( we did however see both adults later that day perched alongside their young. We checked in for 12 consecutive days (I believe) on the owls to track their development and movements, during this time I was blessed to observe the adult owls Hunting, bathing and just going about their daily activities. I also got to watch the young owls learn how to fly and hunt, I wasn’t able to photograph much of it as I didn’t want to interfere with nature’s process, It was a treat I’ll always hold close)

Observation Details: Adorable screech owl found sitting so close to the road that I almost hit it.  Very lethargic, but it has a decent grip and can stay upright, so I have it in the car (at work) and will call the rehab folks at 8:00AM.  8:30AM rehab pickup on the way. 9:20AM picked up by an Evelyn Alexander rehab volunteer.  Update 2/10:  The owl is doing better!  It does have some head trauma, but it is on anti-inflammatory medications and is accepting food on forceps. Update 2/12: The little trooper continues to improve and is eating on its own.  Awesome! Update 2/15:  Great news! The owl has made a "miraculous" recovery and will be released tomorrow (2/16) in the same general area in which it was found. Godspeed little bud.
Ridiculous camouflage.   In awe of this sleepy little bird.

Locality: Custer and Hawley Roads, Custer, Michigan, US (43.876, -86.216)

Observation Details: Wow wow wow! Continuing cutie! I first found the bird in its usual spot. I left and then returned to find the bird gone. While I was looking I was hearing all these weird noises from Mockingbird that I hadn’t heard before but failed to put two into together. To make a long story short, when I check the tree from another angle I realized that he’s mocking bird noises were alarm calls and that the eastern screech owl was sitting right out in the open! I’ve never had such good luck at one of these birds. It sat there for about 35 minutes, before it flew off when my mom called (how great, right?). I quickly relocated it after hearing it sing (trill call) but only narrowed it down to a tree. It then flew again, without me seeing it, and eventually ended up in Wicker’s Creek. Photos to come

Media notes: Taken with the Canon R6 MK2 at ISO 10,000.  No noise reduction needed.
Observation Details: Red and gray seen.  The red morph is likely the female and the gray morph is the male.  This has been my presumption for the last several weeks based on observation of behaviour.  While I have not seen them side by side, the male is the one that vigourously defends the territory and it's always the gray morph that is doing that.  But until I see the two of them side by side, I will not draw any final conclusion.  Reverse siize dimorphism between male and female owls is common where the female is always larger than the male.   It may be sublter in screech owls but once they are perched together you can see the difference (many opportunities to see this at Mud Lake and elsewhere over the years).

Wow wow wow! Continuing cutie! I first found the bird in its usual spot. I left and then returned to find the bird gone. While I was looking I was hearing all these weird noises from Mockingbird that I hadn’t heard before but failed to put two into together. To make a long story short, when I check the tree from another angle I realized that he’s mocking bird noises were alarm calls and that the eastern screech owl was sitting right out in the open! I’ve never had such good luck at one of these birds. It sat there for about 35 minutes, before it flew off when my mom called (how great, right?). I quickly relocated it after hearing it sing (trill call) but only narrowed it down to a tree. It then flew again, without me seeing it, and eventually ended up in Wicker’s Creek. Photos to come
Continuing. Thank you for other birders who pointed out the location.

Locality: Hollis Brookline High School (restricted during school hours)

Observation Details: I was traveling on Wilson Creek Road headed north just before Dalton Hill Road when I observed the grey-morph Eastern Screech Owl in the middle of the road on the yellow stripe that had been hit by a car.  I thought that it was a bag of garbage at first and then realized that it might be an owl.  This was about 6:45 am.  I turned around and found the owl standing up-right on the pavement.  I pulled over and decided that I must scoop it up with a blanket and have it covered in case it was injured.  This is such a busy County Highway, if I hadn't picked it up, it would have been killed for sure.  I contacted ECO Andrew Kostuk of the NYS DEC who said that he would meet me at my workplace in Cortland, NY.  I met up with ECO Kostuk, who stated that it was good that I picked up the owl.  He took the owl to the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic to see if they could help it.  ECO Kostuk told me that Cornell said the owl was alert and that they thought that it would have a full recovery.  Hopefully, it can be released back in to the wild.  Just an update concerning this Screech Owl, I have spoken with ECO Kostuk and the Screech Owl did have a broken wing and was operated on at the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic.  The owl survived the surgery and responded well and was then taken to a certified wildlife rehabilitator.  The owl was able to make a full recovery and am happy to say was released back in to the wild.

This is such a busy County Highway, if I hadn't picked it up, it would have been killed for sure.  I contacted ECO Andrew Kostuk of the NYS DEC who said that he would meet me at my workplace in Cortland, NY.  I met up with ECO Kostuk, who stated that it was good that I picked up the owl.  He took the owl to the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic to see if they could help it.  ECO Kostuk told me that Cornell said the owl was alert and that they thought that it would have a full recovery.  Hopefully, it can be released back in to the wild.  Just an update concerning this Screech Owl, I have spoken with ECO Kostuk and the Screech Owl did have a broken wing and was operated on at the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic.  The owl survived the surgery and responded well and was then taken to a certified wildlife rehabilitator.  The owl was able to make a full recovery and am happy to say was released back in to the wild.

Owl sitting in magnolia tree near owl box

Every winter for the last 4 years I have had an Eastern Screech Owl show up. I call him the fair weather owl since he is only around on nice days. When spring arrives the owl disappears and I wonder if I will ever see it again. This year it seems to be around more than usual but still not consistent. I put up an owl box hoping to attract tenants with no luck. Yesterday I went for a walk at home in the woods and noticed fair weather owl was enjoying the sun. I do not walk under the tree when he is home so that I do not bother him. He jumps back in the hole if you are seen. Maybe I should call him shy owl. I continued my usual walk. There is a tree that I always walk by and I think if I was an owl that would be a perfect home. Well, it was years in the making but yesterday was the day. There was a second owl in the dream owl tree. It must have been my lucky day as no one is home today except me awaiting another lucky day... - Eastern Screech Owl - Madison County - 3/10/18

EASO! Nick spoke his red morph into existence. We were able to put the scope on it and got incredible looks as we happened to be close already. Assuming it was close to a nest cavity, we both looked through the scope for a minute or two before altering our course to walk around rather than past it. Very cool.

Wow wow wow! Continuing cutie! I first found the bird in its usual spot. I left and then returned to find the bird gone. While I was looking I was hearing all these weird noises from Mockingbird that I hadn’t heard before but failed to put two into together. To make a long story short, when I check the tree from another angle I realized that he’s mocking bird noises were alarm calls and that the eastern screech owl was sitting right out in the open! I’ve never had such good luck at one of these birds. It sat there for about 35 minutes, before it flew off when my mom called (how great, right?). I quickly relocated it after hearing it sing (trill call) but only narrowed it down to a tree. It then flew again, without me seeing it, and eventually ended up in Wicker’s Creek. Photos to come

Screech-owls have been at this location for at least a year or so. They apparently nested as presumed family groups of 3 and 4 birds have been seen. Two individuals were seen every night over the holiday period. They are very tame and seem to be feeding on moths attracted to the backyard lights. My son reports they are still there as of this report (Jan 15). The nest site is probably in a stump of a tree in a neighbor's yard. My son put up an owl nest box with the hopes of keeping them around. Photos will be added.

Gray morph (female) perched at entrance to nest box much of the day, while red morph (male) perched in a tree approximately 40 ft from nest box.  At approximately 20:15 the two owls both trilled back and forth.  The male then flew from his perch followed shortly by the female.  The female returned to the nest box briefly about 25 minutes later, then subsequently left the nest box and flew back again approximately 3 minutes later and perched just inside the nest box.  During this last time we could hear a number of calls from owlets inside the box.
She survived last night's thunderstorms.

Observation Details: I was traveling on Wilson Creek Road headed north just before Dalton Hill Road when I observed the grey-morph Eastern Screech Owl in the middle of the road on the yellow stripe that had been hit by a car.  I thought that it was a bag of garbage at first and then realized that it might be an owl.  This was about 6:45 am.  I turned around and found the owl standing up-right on the pavement.  I pulled over and decided that I must scoop it up with a blanket and have it covered in case it was injured.  This is such a busy County Highway, if I hadn't picked it up, it would have been killed for sure.  I contacted ECO Andrew Kostuk of the NYS DEC who said that he would meet me at my workplace in Cortland, NY.  I met up with ECO Kostuk, who stated that it was good that I picked up the owl.  He took the owl to the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic to see if they could help it.  ECO Kostuk told me that Cornell said the owl was alert and that they thought that it would have a full recovery.  Hopefully, it can be released back in to the wild.  Just an update concerning this Screech Owl, I have spoken with ECO Kostuk and the Screech Owl did have a broken wing and was operated on at the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic.  The owl survived the surgery and responded well and was then taken to a certified wildlife rehabilitator.  The owl was able to make a full recovery and am happy to say was released back in to the wild.

Observation Details: feeding young.  Parents continue to provide prey to nest box.  Observed male at 6:45 pm, he flew off at 7:15 as short distance.   Female appeared in box opening at 8.  She was very alert and appeared to be tracking the male.  They were both trilling. At 8:05 she started to weave and bob in the box opening, then disappeared back into the box as the male came from right to left and directly into box at speed.  Put Luke Skywalker and the Jedi to shame.  He flew off shortly thereafter.  At 8:15 the female flew off.  Have observed this tag team feeding of young most evenings.

I saw a bird fly by and immediately knew it was an owl. It looked much smaller than a typical Great Horned Owl, which piqued my curiosity. I pursued it and was able to find it fairly quickly. It was perched on top of a tree and watched as I took a few pictures. It briefly called, but otherwise remained silent. Notice the yellowish color at the base of the bill, unlike the Western which tends to have blackish or dark gray at the base of the bill. Coordinates: (31.3628430, -100.4709249).

Media notes: last two of four chicks to fledge.  Fledged at 8:10 and 8:40 respectively.
Observation Details: Last two of the four chicks fledged this evening.  At 8:10 and 8:40 respectively.  Thought had fledged last night with the first two as this morning and throughout the day there was no activity or sign of owls.  That is until 6 pm.  Spotted chick in nest box opening. Joined by a sibling.  A parent, most likely the female from the trilling I have become so familiar with, began trilling.  The parents did not feed the birds and the trilling was, I think, enticing the two remaining chicks to fledge.  The trilling became louder.  After one chick fledged, the trilling became louder and moved closer to the nest box.  The last one was quite reluctant.  The chicks flew off in the direction of the trills.  The trills were a beacon, I think:  "come this way."  It was too dark to record the final chick fledge but observed with binos.  This awesome moment came with mixed feelings and followed up with a Scotch, neat.  An incredible journey.  Six months four days since the male chick (Dr. Who) took up residence in the nest box.  Four healthy chicks and attentive, experienced parents.  One word:  Breathtaking.

One bird on the ground in the playground mulch was tearing apart and eating something in its talons. Did not see the parents, though they had been seen recently by others. My photos make the birds appear more brightly lit than they were to the naked eye, but I should note that I did not use flash photography, just very high ISO and a very slow shutter speed.

Observation Details: Finally got one - first of the year! Responded to playback before flying out of the woods into some nearby trees where it continued to call back to the recording. I slowly crept up to where it was perched and got my phone out to record it's calls. After recording it a few times I played the recording again and it flew up to a branch not more than 6 feet away from me! I decided to attempt some flash photos with my phone, assuming it would spook and fly away immediately, but it didn't move, it just sat there and stared at the light. At this point I could see that it was a beautiful red morph, and based in the higher pitched call, probably a female. I took some video of it and then decided to go get the camera. Ran all the way back to the house and all the way back out to the spot (apparently I haven't learned to always bring the camera with me). When I returned, I played the recording again to relocate it. Sure enough, within a few seconds it emerged from it's hiding spot and flew right up to a nearby tree in the open. This time I was ready and snapped some killer shots! It moved to another great perch to pose for some more stunning shots. At this point I texted Mom to come out and see it. She and Susannah came out and found me. Again, I used playback to lure it back in close - and REALLY close! It swooped in and landed in a shrub less than 4 feet away from us in plain sight (with flashlights shining on it). It sat there for a minute or two while we kept silent and watched. We waited for it to fly off before going back inside. Such a neat moment!

Heard one at 5:50 AM as we were entering OWL position 1.3 and the second one at 5:59 at OWL position 3.7. Both were calling spontaneously in a rather soft low monotone easy to miss.  Then encountered two more calling spontaneously at OWL position 2.5 was able to take photos. It was about 6:25 AM  which is about five minutes before sunrise and the owl remained in position until at least 6:37 AM. I did call it after I heard the two calling together and recorded them. Still there at 6:42 AM. I approach the L and squeaked with my lips so it would look at me and took some more photos. As I walked away he was still there calling.  I did not hear or see the second OWL after I started photographing them.

Observation Details: 1 flew from the nest box under the bridge and onto a perch on the east side of the bridge. Robins, grackles and blackbirds alternatively mobbed, but the owl was largely unflappable. Eventually, it flew under the bridge and perched for a minute or two before returning to the nest box. The other member of the pair was calling first from the east and then from the stand of trees south of the bridge. The photo "8.jpg" is from this evening. Comparing to "13.jpg" from the previous night, both the ear tufts and chest markings appear different, so I would say these are the two birds, but I could not tell you which bird is which sex.

Perched against the trunk of a sapling right by the bike path. Pointed out by another birder, Rob. Even though I didn't approach it, it went into its cryptic posture when I made eye contact with it. I snapped a couple pics, and then I left it alone, because several Blue Jays and a Cooper's Hawk were nearby, and I didn't want any harm to come to the owl. The owl was really frightened when the Cooper's hawk flew past it. The Coop thankfully didn't notice the owl, otherwise the owl certainly would have flushed. It was a cute little owl, and there was a cavity about in a tree maybe four feet away from where it was perched. I wonder if it has a nest in that hole.

Wow! The first time I've run into a screech-owl randomly in the woods. It was along the trail that leads to the back of Arrowhead Lake, to a blind. I first noticed a mixed flock of birds furiously scolding something and saw the owl from a distance. I approached as the mobbing continued and the bird didn't move, but did assume a defensive posture. I took a few photos then backed off. Was still there when I passed the tree again. The mob included titmice, chickadees, Chipping Sparrows, both kinglets, bluebirds, sapsuckers, a flicker, a Winter Wren, Pine Warblers, Yellow-rumped Warblers, and Carolina Wrens.

Heard one at 5:50 AM as we were entering OWL position 1.3 and the second one at 5:59 at OWL position 3.7. Both were calling spontaneously in a rather soft low monotone easy to miss.  Then encountered two more calling spontaneously at OWL position 2.5 was able to take photos. It was about 6:25 AM  which is about five minutes before sunrise and the owl remained in position until at least 6:37 AM. I did call it after I heard the two calling together and recorded them. Still there at 6:42 AM. I approach the L and squeaked with my lips so it would look at me and took some more photos. As I walked away he was still there calling.  I did not hear or see the second OWL after I started photographing them.

We were walking along the road by the nature center towards the lake and I noticed there was a Screech Owl sitting right next to the road only 6 feet off the ground in a small tree. It was AMAZING!!! Beautiful red phase. The details in the feathers was so vivid since we were so close. My brother got amazing pics of it. People were walking and jogging right past the Owl and it didn't even open its eyes. The only time it open and looked alert is when a large dog walked by and barked but the Owl still didn't move. There was a young couple in the Pine stand looking for Owls so I ran over and grabbed them and they couldn't believe it. They ran home to get their camera too.

Tied with BLGR for bird of the day. We stopped to check a couple of warblers that were just above eye-level in the woods (they were YRWA), and when I put my bins down, I saw an oddly shaped rust-colored blob on one of the branches. EASO! Nick spoke his red morph into existence. We were able to put the scope on it and got incredible looks as we happened to be close already. Assuming it was close to a nest cavity, we both looked through the scope for a minute or two before altering our course to walk around rather than past it. Very cool.

Surveying for nocturnal insects and was shocked when this owl randomly appeared in the tree right in front of me. Had my macro lens for insects on; wasn't anticipating such a close owl encounter. Ran a half mile back to my car to grab my other lens and ran all the way back. By some miracle, the owl was still perched nearby, less than about ten feet off the trail, which allowed for photos. Flew further into the vegetation after a relatively clear photo, and I let it go so it could get back to hunting away from my light. Completely silent; never vocalized once. No playback used. Red morph, the first of this morph for the nature trail.

Observation Details: feeding young.  Parents continue to provide prey to nest box.  Observed male at 6:45 pm, he flew off at 7:15 as short distance.   Female appeared in box opening at 8.  She was very alert and appeared to be tracking the male.  They were both trilling. At 8:05 she started to weave and bob in the box opening, then disappeared back into the box as the male came from right to left and directly into box at speed.  Put Luke Skywalker and the Jedi to shame.  He flew off shortly thereafter.  At 8:15 the female flew off.  Have observed this tag team feeding of young most evenings.

Media notes: Close up.  Male perched near nest box.  Nest with young.
Observation Details: Nest box with young.  Over several days the male has perched in nest box opening for most of the day.  Based on last years observations, this indicates that chicks are present in the next box.  Predicted that when the trees have leafed out he would leave the nest and perch nearby. When he wasn't in the next box opening this morning I checked the perch he used last year at this time.  An American Beech.  Yep, he was there, same branch next to the trunk.  See photos.

Some family members got to see him as well before he eventually flew away into the trees to the northwest.

Finally got one - first of the year! Responded to playback before flying out of the woods into some nearby trees where it continued to call back to the recording. I slowly crept up to where it was perched and got my phone out to record it's calls. After recording it a few times I played the recording again and it flew up to a branch not more than 6 feet away from me! I decided to attempt some flash photos with my phone, assuming it would spook and fly away immediately, but it didn't move, it just sat there and stared at the light. At this point I could see that it was a beautiful red morph, and based in the higher pitched call, probably a female. I took some video of it and then decided to go get the camera. Ran all the way back to the house and all the way back out to the spot (apparently I haven't learned to always bring the camera with me). When I returned, I played the recording again to relocate it. Sure enough, within a few seconds it emerged from it's hiding spot and flew right up to a nearby tree in the open. This time I was ready and snapped some killer shots! It moved to another great perch to pose for some more stunning shots. At this point I texted Mom to come out and see it. She and Susannah came out and found me. Again, I used playback to lure it back in close - and REALLY close! It swooped in and landed in a shrub less than 4 feet away from us in plain sight (with flashlights shining on it). It sat there for a minute or two while we kept silent and watched. We waited for it to fly off before going back inside. Such a neat moment!

I heard two at 6:50 AM which were likely the pair that I named the red and gray pair at OWL position 2.3.  I could see both fly in the dark when I then called them and was able to take a few pictures with my flashlight when one landed in a tree directly in front of me. While I was calling the ESO a fairly large bird flew  directly over my head and it had the size and shape of a great horned owl. This is close to where I saw it and then  photographed it with a second GHOW. I don’t believe it was a heron as it had overall dark undersides so it was not a barn owl which to my eye also seems to have more slender and longer wings than the great horned owl. It flew in from behind me and disappeared to the south directly down along the path. However I will not report it as I really am not sure. It’s possible that I attracted it by calling the screech owl. I called the GH0W as I walked back but got no response.

Observation Details: Perched against the trunk of a sapling right by the bike path. Pointed out by another birder, Rob. Even though I didn't approach it, it went into its cryptic posture when I made eye contact with it. I snapped a couple pics, and then I left it alone, because several Blue Jays and a Cooper's Hawk were nearby, and I didn't want any harm to come to the owl. The owl was really frightened when the Cooper's hawk flew past it. The Coop thankfully didn't notice the owl, otherwise the owl certainly would have flushed. It was a cute little owl, and there was a cavity about in a tree maybe four feet away from where it was perched. I wonder if it has a nest in that hole.

Media notes: First day owlets seen at my backyard owl box.
Observation Details: Saw resident adult screech-owl in my backyard owl box at the beginning of the viewing session.  Later saw two heads poking out of box and saw that they were owlets.  Nice surprise...our expected owlets revealed themselves on Mothers Day.  One adult owl was first sighted in the box on 01NOV2018 and was seen almost daily at sunrise and sunset.  Around 15MAR, stopped seeing owl but would hear its whinnies from the box.  Possibly sitting on eggs.  About mid-April, started seeing adult owl again at the box.  Soon saw two adult owls flying in and out of the box just after sunset, possibly feeding the young.  Pictures of owlets taken later this day (12MAY), while photos of adult owls are from earlier sightings.  Believe the larger grey adult is female, the smaller brown-grey is male.

One parent was Grey Phase and one parent was Red Phase.

The Eastern Screech-owls were discovered within a Camp in Myles Standish State Forest. They were perching in primarily Pitch pines and Eastern White pines located within the Pine Barren forest. They were observed in the same location multiple nights in a row being heard around 8:30 each time. Seemed curious of my presence and didn't move far. With assistance after the fact I was able to identify from photos both juvenile and adults.

Observation Details: Red phase individual reappeared today after being absent since the initial discovery day on 9/19.  Seen by 5 other people, one of whom came from as far away as Bailey, homing in on the original eBird report which I now know was too specific.  Today the owl seemed unconcerned about humans who stayed a reasonable distance away.  Likewise, seemed unconcerned about both Red and White-breasted Nuthatches that came to yell at it inches away. Scared down the cavity instantly by an incoming, screaming Blue Jay.  Paid serious attention to fox squirrels that came under the roost tree.  Birders, reading this, DO NOT HASSLE THIS BIRD, PLEASE!  If you do, this will be the last position of a potential target bird I will ever post to eBird.

Observation Details: WOW! I've been out every night for the past month and many nights before that attempting to photograph this species. I've heard only two during this time. Tonight, about 5:20 PM EST, I stopped and did one call of playback and a screech-owl started singing loudly back to me. I waited quietly hoping it'd come closer but it sounded like it was staying put. Thinking this was going to be another heard only encounter, I decided to turn on the flashlight and scan far back in the trees to see if I could see a silhouette anywhere. To my shock, the screech-owl was sitting directly in front of me about fifteen feet away, if that! I had to try very hard to stay quiet! He sat patiently and let me take lots of pictures. It's crazy how small they are; it puts it in perspective when one is sitting right near you. I had a spotlight (which would have gotten much better pictures) but since he was so close I didn't use it because I didn't want to burn his eyes!! I had to make due with the flashlight and flash but I think it worked great. After about three minutes, he hopped off his perch and flew to some nearby vegetation. He was still very close, but I decided to leave so he could get to hunting for the night. Now I have added the screech-owl to my photography list!! I am so excited! Finally! Thank you, screech-owl!

Media notes: two remains chicks of four.  The other two fledged this evening.
Observation Details: And then there were four.  Two chicks fledged this evening.  A fourth chick appeared in nest box opening. Mom flew from nest at 7:30 pm and perched nearby trilling.  At 8:07 mom returned and feed one chick.  Shortly afterward the chick that was feed, left the nest box and perched on branch in front of nest box opening.  At 8:10 it flew off (see video).  Approx. 8 to 10 minutes later a second chick climbed to the top of the nest box, pacing from side to side.  Mom returned briefly and perched on branch in front of nest box then flew off.  Shortly afterward the second chick flew off as well.  At that point, a parent returned and feed the two remains chicks in the nest box.  What a great evening.  I had read that parents at times withhold food to get the chicks to fledge.  This seemed the case this evening.

Observation Details: At least one identifiable adult. At least five juvenile. Grey. We first saw them at about 10:30 when we first entered the woods - no binoculars. There were nuthatches, robins, chickadees, downies, and several other small song birds making a commotion, so I looked to see if they were trying to upset an owl. We spotted two at first, then we left and returned with binns and a camera. We first spotted three, then walked around a bit, came back and there were four. Walked off again, returned to five... walked off yet again and returned to find six all together. By the time we left, the owls were no longer being harassed by the songbirds.

Observation Details: I was traveling on Wilson Creek Road headed north just before Dalton Hill Road when I observed the grey-morph Eastern Screech Owl in the middle of the road on the yellow stripe that had been hit by a car.  I thought that it was a bag of garbage at first and then realized that it might be an owl.  This was about 6:45 am.  I turned around and found the owl standing up-right on the pavement.  I pulled over and decided that I must scoop it up with a blanket and have it covered in case it was injured.  This is such a busy County Highway, if I hadn't picked it up, it would have been killed for sure.  I contacted ECO Andrew Kostuk of the NYS DEC who said that he would meet me at my workplace in Cortland, NY.  I met up with ECO Kostuk, who stated that it was good that I picked up the owl.  He took the owl to the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic to see if they could help it.  ECO Kostuk told me that Cornell said the owl was alert and that they thought that it would have a full recovery.  Hopefully, it can be released back in to the wild.  Just an update concerning this Screech Owl, I have spoken with ECO Kostuk and the Screech Owl did have a broken wing and was operated on at the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic.  The owl survived the surgery and responded well and was then taken to a certified wildlife rehabilitator.  The owl was able to make a full recovery and am happy to say was released back in to the wild.

I was traveling on Wilson Creek Road headed north just before Dalton Hill Road when I observed the grey-morph Eastern Screech Owl in the middle of the road on the yellow stripe that had been hit by a car.  I thought that it was a bag of garbage at first and then realized that it might be an owl.  This was about 6:45 am.  I turned around and found the owl standing up-right on the pavement.  I pulled over and decided that I must scoop it up with a blanket and have it covered in case it was injured.  This is such a busy County Highway, if I hadn't picked it up, it would have been killed for sure.  I contacted ECO Andrew Kostuk of the NYS DEC who said that he would meet me at my workplace in Cortland, NY.  I met up with ECO Kostuk, who stated that it was good that I picked up the owl. Hopefully, it can be released back in to the wild.  Just an update concerning this Screech Owl, I have spoken with ECO Kostuk and the Screech Owl did have a broken wing and was operated on at the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic. Noticed a hole with something in it hoping for a Screech Owl but it turned out to be leaves but I happened to look to the left and noticed some rust coloring and it was an Owl!! It was on the other side of the canal to the right of the "bridge to no-where". I wanted to get in front of it cause I was off to the side and two other Birders walked up. I told them I just found an Owl and I was going to get closer so we all walked over but there was another guy and his dog (off leash) walking the canal path and the Owl got spooked. As soon as I got it in my scope it backed down in to the snag it was looking out of. The couple waited and then left. I waited for about 45-60min for it to come back out. It took the sun coming out for it to make an appearance. It sat there soaking up the last of the sun. A Flicker came flying up to the snag and the Owl backed down in to the hole again. The Flicker almost went down in to the snag but looked in and flew off. The owl didn't come back out while I was there.

Each time I've taken pictures of this owl, it took over an hour of waiting around to get a decent photo.  Usually it is low down in the hole.  In this case, birds and squirrels were back and forth nearby and it raised up to look at them.   (Another time it came up to catch the sun rays.) People should never make noises (or use an owl sound from a bird app) around an owl to get it to react.   It is harassment.  If you can't get a picture, try again another time.

As I was driving through the Edinboro Cemetery, I noticed several BLJAs acting as if they were mobbing an owl hiding in a mature Norway Spruce tree (i.e., they were calling loudly, joined by WBNUs and BCCHs, clustering distain in one general area of the tree.  They were quite alarmed.)  I parked the car and spent about 5 minutes carefully walking around underneath the tree, carefully looking up through the branches. I saw nothing.  I also looked for cast pellets on the ground.  Again nothing.  I even positioned myself so as to have all the branches and boughs silhouetted in the sunlight.  Again nothing.  As I was walking away, the Blue Jays returned while I was still very close, and started mobbing one particular outer spruce bough.  I knew at that point, there had to be a small owl hiding in there because the BLJAs would never have come that close to me otherwise.  Upon closer examination I saw a red-phase Eastern Screech-Owl stretched real tall, hiding in the outermost branches, extremely well hidden.

Observation Details: Finally got one - first of the year! Responded to playback before flying out of the woods into some nearby trees where it continued to call back to the recording. I slowly crept up to where it was perched and got my phone out to record it's calls. After recording it a few times I played the recording again and it flew up to a branch not more than 6 feet away from me! I decided to attempt some flash photos with my phone, assuming it would spook and fly away immediately, but it didn't move, it just sat there and stared at the light. At this point I could see that it was a beautiful red morph, and based in the higher pitched call, probably a female. I took some video of it and then decided to go get the camera. Ran all the way back to the house and all the way back out to the spot (apparently I haven't learned to always bring the camera with me). When I returned, I played the recording again to relocate it. Sure enough, within a few seconds it emerged from it's hiding spot and flew right up to a nearby tree in the open. This time I was ready and snapped some killer shots! It moved to another great perch to pose for some more stunning shots. At this point I texted Mom to come out and see it. She and Susannah came out and found me. Again, I used playback to lure it back in close - and REALLY close! It swooped in and landed in a shrub less than 4 feet away from us in plain sight (with flashlights shining on it). It sat there for a minute or two while we kept silent and watched. We waited for it to fly off before going back inside. Such a neat moment!

I heard two at 6:50 AM which were likely the pair that I named the red and gray pair at OWL position 2.3.  I could see both fly in the dark when I then called them and was able to take a few pictures with my flashlight when one landed in a tree directly in front of me. While I was calling the ESO a fairly large bird flew  directly over my head and it had the size and shape of a great horned owl. This is close to where I saw it and then  photographed it with a second GHOW. I don’t believe it was a heron as it had overall dark undersides so it was not a barn owl which to my eye also seems to have more slender and longer wings than the great horned owl. It flew in from behind me and disappeared to the south directly down along the path. However I will not report it as I really am not sure. It’s possible that I attracted it by calling the screech owl. I called the GH0W as I walked back but got no response.

Our owlets finally fledged from our backyard owl box.  Saw male adult next to smallest owlet in small tree about 10ft from owl box.  Three other owlets were nestled together on a higher branch in a taller tree about 10 more feet away from the box.  The female adult was in a tree next to that one, looking down on the rest of the owls.   We believe the adults are the same ones that raised a batch of owlets in our box last year.  We saw the female back in the box about Nov 1st, and think she laid this batch of eggs at the beginning of March, when she stopped regularly appearing at the box's opening.  The eggs probably hatched at the beginning of April, and we started seeing lots of activity from the male and female at dawn and dusk, when they were likely hunting to feed the hatchlings.  An owlet was first sighted at the opening of the box on May 8th, and the owlets began to perch at the opening on May 10th.  Five days later, they fledged. Pictures will be added here when able.

The owl (s) were seen in the nest box in my back yard. Here is the series of events:  I looked up at 7:37 PM and the owl was there looking out. It looked around until 7:49 PM but then went back down into the box. At 7:50 it appeared again looked around but went down again at 8:00PM. Then came out again at 8:14 and flew away at 8:15. Another owl flew into the box at 8:21, it actually looked around a bit and then went down into the box. But then another owl went in at 8:24. So I believe at this point there are two owls in the box. Watch until 8:32 PM and saw no more activity.

At least one identifiable adult. At least five juvenile. Grey. We first saw them at about 10:30 when we first entered the woods - no binoculars. There were nuthatches, robins, chickadees, downies, and several other small song birds making a commotion, so I looked to see if they were trying to upset an owl. We spotted two at first, then we left and returned with binns and a camera. We first spotted three, then walked around a bit, came back and there were four. Walked off again, returned to five... walked off yet again and returned to find six all together. By the time we left, the owls were no longer being harassed by the songbirds.

I strongly encourage all birders to maintain a safe distance and avoid making a lot of noise while walking in the area.

I was traveling on Wilson Creek Road headed north just before Dalton Hill Road when I observed the grey-morph Eastern Screech Owl in the middle of the road on the yellow stripe that had been hit by a car.  I thought that it was a bag of garbage at first and then realized that it might be an owl.  This was about 6:45 am.  I turned around and found the owl standing up-right on the pavement.  I pulled over and decided that I must scoop it up with a blanket and have it covered in case it was injured.  This is such a busy County Highway, if I hadn't picked it up, it would have been killed for sure.  I contacted ECO Andrew Kostuk of the NYS DEC who said that he would meet me at my workplace in Cortland, NY.  I met up with ECO Kostuk, who stated that it was good that I picked up the owl.  He took the owl to the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic to see if they could help it.  ECO Kostuk told me that Cornell said the owl was alert and that they thought that it would have a full recovery.  Hopefully, it can be released back in to the wild.  Just an update concerning this Screech Owl, I have spoken with ECO Kostuk and the Screech Owl did have a broken wing and was operated on at the Cornell University Veterinary Clinic.  The owl survived the surgery and responded well and was then taken to a certified wildlife rehabilitator.  The owl was able to make a full recovery and am happy to say was released back in to the wild.

Fishing owl has now been captured on trail camera for two weeks every night and could be carrying food to young given the time of year. Photo on eBird.

Owl fishing in riffle. Appears to fly up with fish in bill. Photo captured by trail cam, which was positioned on this spot starting on May 30, so it is unknown how long the owl has been fishing here. Owl has fished every night since May 30. It is noted that no screech owl vocalizations have been heard in April or May, whereas frequent tremolos were heard during March. Perhaps it could be guessed that April was incubation month and May was nestling month, suggesting that this fishing owl could be carrying food to young, either nestlings or fledglings. Finally got one - first of the year! Responded to playback before flying out of the woods into some nearby trees where it continued to call back to the recording. I slowly crept up to where it was perched and got my phone out to record it's calls. After recording it a few times I played the recording again and it flew up to a branch not more than 6 feet away from me! I decided to attempt some flash photos with my phone, assuming it would spook and fly away immediately, but it didn't move, it just sat there and stared at the light. At this point I could see that it was a beautiful red morph, and based in the higher pitched call, probably a female. I took some video of it and then decided to go get the camera. Ran all the way back to the house and all the way back out to the spot (apparently I haven't learned to always bring the camera with me). When I returned, I played the recording again to relocate it. Sure enough, within a few seconds it emerged from it's hiding spot and flew right up to a nearby tree in the open. This time I was ready and snapped some killer shots! It moved to another great perch to pose for some more stunning shots. At this point I texted Mom to come out and see it. She and Susannah came out and found me. Again, I used playback to lure it back in close - and REALLY close! It swooped in and landed in a shrub less than 4 feet away from us in plain sight (with flashlights shining on it). It sat there for a minute or two while we kept silent and watched. We waited for it to fly off before going back inside. Such a neat moment!

Walking down the driveway and looked up at one of my wood duck boxes to find a very unusual and welcome surprise.  A red phased eastern screech is roosting in the box.  I went to get my camera and unfortunately as I slowly approached to get a clear picture unobstructed from branches, it ducked back inside.  Definitely a screech, complete with ear tufts.  Will try to get some kind of picture if it comes to the entrance again, although staying further back on the driveway.

Our owlets finally fledged from our backyard owl box.  Saw male adult next to smallest owlet in small tree about 10ft from owl box.  Three other owlets were nestled together on a higher branch in a taller tree about 10 more feet away from the box.  The female adult was in a tree next to that one, looking down on the rest of the owls.   We believe the adults are the same ones that raised a batch of owlets in our box last year.  We saw the female back in the box about Nov 1st, and think she laid this batch of eggs at the beginning of March, when she stopped regularly appearing at the box's opening.  The eggs probably hatched at the beginning of April, and we started seeing lots of activity from the male and female at dawn and dusk, when they were likely hunting to feed the hatchlings.  An owlet was first sighted at the opening of the box on May 8th, and the owlets began to perch at the opening on May 10th.  Five days later, they fledged. Pictures will be added here when able.
